Motivations

Motivation number 1: seeing a function in a textbook

\[ \frac{\Delta N}{\Delta T} = rN(\frac{K-N}{K}) \]

You see this equation in Section 53.3 of your textbook, with a nice explanation of the different parts of the equation. Often, however, there isnâ€™t a good explanation of the parts. And even if there is a good explanation, it is really easy to just give a very perfunctory look at the equation and read of the section (ever since Stephen Jay Gould used â€œdesultoryâ€ instead of â€œperfunctoryâ€ in one of his essays, these two words have been a favorite of mine. Desultory means to jump around, as in a conversation. Perfunctory means to do something mindlessly).

A spreadsheet is a wicked valuable learning tool for self-discovery of the behavior of a function like this. By behavior, I mean what a graph of the function looks like, if we change the parameters (the variables on the right hand side). This activity is an introduction to self-discovery.

Motivation number 2: Quantitative vs.Â Qualitative Science

Biologists frequently observe population growth and decline in some species, and a major goal in ecology is to discover the mechanisms regulating this growth or decline. For example, if oak trees in southern Maine have a large mast event (dropping lots of acorns), then we might expect an increase in the chipmunk population the next year using the logic that adult chipmunks turn food into babies. But this is all very qualitative. Good science often requires abstracting some specific but qualitative phenomonenon into a general, quantitative model. In this lab, weâ€™re going to numerical self-discovery to explore some simple, quantitative models of population size.

The logistic model of population growth

Letâ€™s start with the logistic model of population growth. Your textbook presents this equation to you.

\[ \frac{\Delta N}{\Delta T} = rN(\frac{K-N}{K}) \]

Here we arenâ€™t concerned with deriving the equation or with the assumptions of using this function to model something biological. We are concerned only with the behavior of the function itself. Iâ€™ll leave derivation and assumptions to other worksheets.

You see this function in your textbook or on the blackboard. How do you use a spreadsheet to self-discover? That is, how do you get the equation into a spreadsheet?

  1. First, be sure to think of this equation as a function similar to a function in a spreadsheet. A function has inputs and outputs. The parameters \(r\), \(N\), and \(K\) on the right hand side (rhs) of the function are the inputs. \(\frac{\Delta N}{\Delta T}\) on the left hand side (lhs) is the output. If you use some specific set of numbers for the inputs, then do the simple math, you get a specific value for the output
  2. Second, what is all the stuff in the equation? The parameters on the rhs of the equal sign are
  • \(r\) is the intrinsic growth rate. Weâ€™ll define this better in a minute.
  • \(N\) is population size, that is the number of individuals
  • \(K\) is the equilibrium population size or â€œcarrying capacityâ€.

Q2 â€“ When you come across phrases like â€œequilibrium population sizeâ€, stop for a moment to think about what this means. Which of these responses is closest to what youâ€™re thinking?

The left hand side (lhs) of the equation is the output. The output is just a single number but there are three things on the lhs

  • \(N\) is defined above
  • \(T\) is time. The unit of time (minutes, days, generations) isnâ€™t specified and doesnâ€™t matter here.
  • \(\Delta\) is not a variable it is a symbol meaning â€œchange inâ€ and used to specify how one variable changes given change in another variable. So \(\frac{\Delta N}{\Delta T}\), which is read as â€œdelta en over delta teeâ€ is the change in population size over time. Any change in something over time is a rate, so \(\frac{\Delta N}{\Delta T}\) is the rate of population growth.

Rearrange the equation

In the thought question (Q1) above, I asked you to envision how the population size (N) changes over time. But the logistic function above models the rate of growth, not the population size. So letâ€™s do some algebra on this equation, to model population size as a function of time if the population is growing logistically. That is, we want to create a plot with \(N\) on the \(y\)-axis and \(Time\) on the \(x\)-axis.

Letâ€™s expand \(\Delta N\)

\[ \Delta N = N_{t+1} - N_t \]

Wait, what is â€œtâ€ and â€œt+1â€? \(t\) is a point in time (any point in time) and \(t+1\) is one time unit after time \(t\). For example, if \(t\) is day 30 and the unit of time is â€œone dayâ€ then \(t+1\) is day 31.

So \(N_{t+1} - N_t\) is the change in count after a single time step (a day, a month, a year). Here we say that \(t\) â€œindexes timeâ€.

For this assignment, letâ€™s think of \(t\) as indexing a generation (the time from parents to offspring). So \(\Delta N\) is the change in count over a single generation.

Since the change in time (\(\Delta T\)) is one unit, this means

\[ \frac{\Delta N}{\Delta T} = \frac{N_{t+1} - N_t}{1} = N_{t+1} - N_t \]

Substitute this in to the lhs of the logistic equation

\[ N_{t+1} - N_t = rN_t(\frac{K-N_t}{K}) \]

and re-arrange â€¦

\[N_{t+1} = N_t + rN_t(\frac{K-N_t}{K})\]

Now we have a function for the count at any generation. Another, and maybe more useful for mental exploration, way to write this is

\[N_{t+1} = N_t + rN_t(1 - \frac{N_t}{K})\] This is the equation that you want to numerically self-discover with Google sheets

Mental Self-Discovery

Letâ€™s think about the parameter on the rhs and how they should effect the output (\(N_{t+1}\)).

  1. First, note that the count at generation \(t+1\) is the sum of two things: the count at generation \(t\) and some value that is itself a function of the count at generation \(t\). Think about this, without any information other than the count, we would expect the count in the next generation to be the count in the previous generation. But if we have more information (the intrinsic growth rate \(r\) or the equilibrium population size \(K\)) then we can refine this expectation.
  2. The equilbrium population size \(K\) is the size that we would expect the population to be given a certain level of resources (the amount of food, the amount of space for nesting, etc.). How does \(K\) modify \(N_t\)?. Think about this as

\[N_t(1 - \frac{N_t}{K})\]

\(K\) is a theoretical population size so its value must be a number between zero and infinity. It canâ€™t really be infinity but its useful to think about what happens if \(K\) were infinity. And if there are any resources, it canâ€™t be zero.

Q3 If \(K = \infty\) (â€œK is infinityâ€), what is the value of \(N_t(1 - \frac{N_t}{K})\)?

Q4 If \(K = \infty\), then the logistic growth equation reduces to?

The correct equation is known as the exponential growth model. Again, \(K\) can never really be infinity but its useful to think of exponential growth as a special case of logistic growth. And that when the population size is far below the equilibrium population size, growth should be effectively exponential.

Q5 If \(K = N_t\), what is the value of \(N_t(1 - \frac{N_t}{K})\)?

Q6 If \(K = N_t\), then the logistic growth equation reduces to?

Stop and think, does your answer to Q6 make sense?

Numerical Self-Discovery

Students in Biology are inundated with equations both from Biology classes and from classes such as Physics and Chemistry. For most of us, these equations are pretty hard to really understand, even if we can do the math. By â€œunderstandâ€, I mean, to treat the equation as a function, with inputs (the parameters) and outputs (what the function equates to given the parameters) and to have a picture in oneâ€™s head of how this function behaves. By â€œbehaveâ€, I mean what the function looks like and how â€œwhat it looks likeâ€ depends on the parameters. A spreadsheet is a terrific way to self-discover the behavior of a function. This worksheet is a step-by-step guide on how to do this. The skills learned here should be transferable to any function, although a spreadsheet might not be the perfect tool for some more complex functions.

Explore the logistic model in a spreadsheet

Open Google Sheets.

  1. First set up a row of column labels containing all the variables that we care about (see figure above). This includes a column \(T\) for \(Time\) (or generation) that is not explicitly on the rhs but is there implicitly!
  2. Parameterize the model. We do this by setting the values of \(T\), \(N\), \(r\) and \(K\). I inserted â€œ1â€ for \(T\), â€œ50â€ for \(N\), â€œ.1â€ for \(r\) and â€œ1000â€ for \(K\). Donâ€™t worry about the values you insert because the beauty of using a spreadsheet for self-discovery is that you will change these later!
  3. In Cell A3, insert the formula to increase \(T\) by 1 unit.
  4. In Cell B3, insert the formula for \(N_{t+1}\) (N at time 2) as a function of \(N_t\) (N at time 1). Use the cell address for the values of \(r\) (cell C2) and \(K\) (cell D2) in the formula AND use the $ sign to force this formula to point to cells C2 and D2. Use the logistic equation above to create this formula.
  5. Fill down (about 100 rows) the formulas in Cell A3 and Cell B3. Make sure that the formula in column B always refers to cells C2 for \(r\) and D2 for \(K\).

6. Plot the data with \(N\) on the y-axis and \(Time\) on the x-axis. Click-and-drag to highlight the columns T and N including the labels â€œTâ€ and â€œNâ€. Now choose the menu â€œInsert Chartâ€ then click on chart type and click the chart highlighted in the figure by the light blue line. Then click â€œUse column A as labelsâ€ which makes the values in the column labeled â€œTâ€ the x-axis. The column labeled \(N\) will be the y-axis. 7. Now you have a plot of the function. Now itâ€™s time to explore the function by changing \(r\) or changing \(K\) or changing the initial \(N\). The plot will immediately re-draw in response to these changes. Explore around then come back to the sections below.

    • can \(K\) be a negative value?

More stuff to explore - discover chaos

  1. Set the initial \(T\) to 1, the initial \(N\) to 1, \(r\) to 0.6, and \(K\) to 10000 (that is â€œten thousandâ€).
  2. Now set \(r\) to values above 1 but less than 3. Can you
    • find damped oscillation (see the left figure below)?
    • find a stable limit cycle (see the right figure below)?
    • find chaos (Figure~\(\ref{fig:chaos}\))?
  3. after you find chaos, highlight and copy the set of \(N\) then paste-special the values into a blank column (if you donâ€™t â€œpaste specialâ€ the formula will be pasted into the new cells. Donâ€™t do this, paste the values only by using â€œpaste specialâ€).
  4. now change the initial value of \(N\) by one and again, highlight, then, copy, then paste-special the values into the cells next to the other column you copy and pasted. Compare the values. The first few \(N\) will be nearly the same in both columns but at some point they diverge wildly and are unrelated to each other. This is chaos. It means that the function (the output \(N\)) is highly sensitive to the input values.

Hint: A damped oscillation occurs if \(r\) is between 1 and 2. A stable limit cycle occurs if \(r\) is between 2 and 2.69. Chaos occurs if r > 2.69.

This behavior of the logistic function was discovered by Robert May, Baron May of Oxford. and finally - stochastic models

The models above are deterministic - if the same parameters are entered then \(N\) at time \(T=20\) or \(T=100\) is always precisely the same. Even if the function is chaotic. Real populations are affected by processes that cause \(r\) or \(K\) to change. For example, a particularly heavy winter causes more deaths so \(r\) is smaller or more negative. Or maybe it was a particularly flush year for insect prey so \(K\) increases. For any real population, there will effectively be an infinite number of these deterministic processes affecting \(r\) or \(K\), some in the positive direction and some in the negative direction. Instead of modeling many thousands of deterministic processes affecting \(r\) and \(K\), we combine them all into a single random variable that adds some random amount to \(r\) or to \(K\) each time step. This amount will usually be small but sometimes it will be big. And it will be negative as often as positive. We call this added, random amount noise. We donâ€™t care (at this point) about what causes this noise, we just want to see how the population handles stochastic change in the parameters. A stochastic model is a model that includes random noise in addition to the deterministic component.

How do you add random noise to the model youâ€™ve built? The noise is added to \(r\) or to \(K\) so these should change each time step, just like \(N\). So now the value for \(r\) or \(K\) needs a formula. Iâ€™ll describe this for \(r\). You are on your own for \(K\). The function to add random normal noise to \(r\) is

\[ r_t = \bar{r} + \varepsilon_t \]

\(\bar{r}\) is the mean \(r\) - it is the value that \(r\) will fluctuate around. \(\varepsilon_t\) is the added noise. You will add noise from a normal distribution with mean zero (so it will be negative as often as positive) and standard deviation \(\sigma\).

  1. Highlight the first two rows and insert two rows above these. The header row with the parameter labels should now be in row 3
  2. Two cells above â€œNâ€ insert â€œMeanâ€
  3. One cell above â€œNâ€ insert â€œSDâ€ for standard deviation
  4. Two cells above â€œrâ€ insert some mean value for \(r\), say 0.6
  5. One cell above â€œrâ€ insert some value for the standard deviation - the bigger this value the more \(r\) can change each step. Try 0.1
  6. In the cell for \(r\) at the initial time (C4) insert the formula for \(r_t\) with added random noise, how do you translate the function into a spreadsheet formula?
  7. the answer is â€œ=C$1 + norminv(rand(),0,C$2)â€
  8. Now copy this formula down for all values of \(T\). You should have some variation in \(r\) with most values near .6
  9. Now you also need to modify your formula for \(N\), since it refers only to the value of \(r\) at the initial time, how do you do this?
  10. Correct! click in cell B5 and remove the dollar sign from â€œC$4â€ so that the referred cell â€œmoves downâ€ when copied and pasted
  11. Now highlight cell B5 and click and drag the bounding box to the end of your table. The value of \(N\) now includes a stochastic component.

And, what to do with your new stochastic model? Remember not to change \(r\) by changing the value in cell C4! Instead play around with the Mean and SD. Make the SD as big or bigger than the Mean, either by increasing the SD or making the Mean small. Can you make a population go extinct even though it has a positive mean \(r\)?
